The walrus operator.

Added in python three point eight. Lets you assign inside an expression — combining compute and name the result in one step. Useful in while conditions and if checks where you would otherwise compute the value twice or assign on a separate line.

The shape — name walrus expression — returns the value of the expression and binds it to the name. Always written inside parentheses except in specific positions where the grammar allows it bare.

In code, picture reading lines from a file-like object. The pre-walrus version assigns once, checks, repeats inside a while-true loop. The with-walrus version does it in one condition — while parens line walrus f dot read-line dot strip — assigns and checks in one line.

In an if — also clean for length checks. If parens n walrus l-e-n of data greater-than thirty, then print the message with n.

In list comprehensions — defer expensive calls. Import math. Build a list of y for x drawn from range of five, if parens y walrus math dot square-root of x times ten greater-than three. The walrus computes y once and uses it both in the filter and in the projection.
